{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-template-post-template-tsx","path":"/posts/avoid-using-a-powerful-rm/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"id":"61a089d3-0216-5dde-9ed0-500ed84cca20","html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/4b190/rm-monika.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 56.25%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <picture>\n          <source\n              srcset=\"/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/8ac56/rm-monika.webp 240w,\n/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/d3be9/rm-monika.webp 480w,\n/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/d00b9/rm-monika.webp 800w\"\n              sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n              type=\"image/webp\"\n            />\n          <source\n            srcset=\"/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/09b79/rm-monika.jpg 240w,\n/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/7cc5e/rm-monika.jpg 480w,\n/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/4b190/rm-monika.jpg 800w\"\n            sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n            type=\"image/jpeg\"\n          />\n          <img\n            class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n            src=\"/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/4b190/rm-monika.jpg\"\n            alt=\"rm-monika\"\n            title=\"\"\n            loading=\"lazy\"\n            decoding=\"async\"\n            style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n          />\n        </picture>\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>As we all know, rm is a potent deletion tool in the Linux environment, which can easily lead to the tragic consequence of deleting important files without prompts. I’ve made this mistake myself today, it’s terrifying. I wanted to delete all the files starting with “head”. But somehow I typed <code class=\"language-text\">rm head *</code> instead of <code class=\"language-text\">rm head*</code>. All key files were gone unexpectedly without any prompt.</p>\n<p>After this incident, I took a lot of time to recover the files, and on the other hand, I took some time to seek some protection tricks to avoid this kind of disaster in the future. We’ve got two methods to avoid this kind of disaster:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>force <code class=\"language-text\">rm</code> to output prompts</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell\"><pre class=\"language-shell\"><code class=\"language-shell\">$ <span class=\"token builtin class-name\">alias</span> <span class=\"token function\">rm</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token string\">'rm -i'</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Although this can force a check to be performed whenever a file is being deleted, it is a bit too verbose.</p>\n<ol start=\"2\">\n<li>move the deleted file to the Recycle Bin</li>\n</ol>\n<ul>\n<li>create a script file named <code class=\"language-text\">rm</code> in the <code class=\"language-text\">~/.local/bin</code> directory, and add the following content, give the script file executable permission</li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell\"><pre class=\"language-shell\"><code class=\"language-shell\"><span class=\"token shebang important\">#!/bin/sh</span>\n<span class=\"token function\">mv</span> <span class=\"token variable\">$@</span> ~/.trash/</code></pre></div>\n<ul>\n<li>create the Recycle Bin directory <code class=\"language-text\">~/.trash</code></li>\n</ul>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell\"><pre class=\"language-shell\"><code class=\"language-shell\">$ <span class=\"token function\">mkdir</span> ~/.trash</code></pre></div>\n<p>The advantage is that all deletions are converted to moving to the Recycle Bin <code class=\"language-text\">~/.trash</code>, but some options of <code class=\"language-text\">rm</code> are not supported by <code class=\"language-text\">mv</code>.</p>\n<p>The current solution is not perfect yet, we need further exploration.</p>","fields":{"slug":"/posts/2010-04-13---Avoid-Using-a-Powerful-\"rm\"//posts/avoid-using-a-powerful-rm","tagSlugs":["/tag/linux-system/","/tag/shell/"]},"frontmatter":{"date":"2010-04-13T11:20:00.000Z","description":"a powerful rm command may lead to unexpected deletion of files, we need some protection tricks.","tags":["Linux System","Shell"],"title":"Avoid Using a Powerful \"rm\"","socialImage":{"publicURL":"/static/bf3c120997e36184062582ec81848060/rm-monika.jpg"}}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/posts/2010-04-13---Avoid-Using-a-Powerful-\"rm\"//posts/avoid-using-a-powerful-rm"}},"staticQueryHashes":["251939775","288581551","401334301"],"slicesMap":{}}